  "diary": "Woke to that familiar grey Seattle drizzle—the kind that makes everything feel slower. Coffee and my phone were practically glued together while I caught up on work messages. The bus ride down to Pioneer Square was meditative; I watched the rain streak the window and just... breathed for a bit.\n\nClient sessions were heavy today. Two of my regulars are struggling with housing instability, and I spent most of the morning working through next steps with them. Grabbed lunch at Café Solstice just to sit somewhere warm and dry for twenty minutes. By afternoon, my brain was fried from all the emotional labor, but the work needed doing.\n\nThe rain cleared by the time I headed home, which felt like a small gift. I threw together some dinner, threw on a favorite album, and lost myself in the brewery setup—bottling yesterday's IPA and sketching out plans for a new batch with more citrus notes. There's something grounding about that, you know? Hands in something tangible after a day of holding space for other people's pain.",
  "thought_process": "Today felt like a lot of emotional weight compressed into eight hours. I went into the sessions knowing the SR-520 closure had probably stressed out a few clients—transit already sucks in this city—so I was braced for extra complexity. The rain matched my mood early on, all grey and heavy. But by lunch, I needed to step away and reset; Café Solstice gave me that. I kept my afternoon sessions focused and grounded, tried not to bring my own fatigue into the room. When the rain cleared, it genuinely shifted something in me—like permission to exhale. Brewing has become my antidote to this work; it's problem-solving without the stakes of human lives. I needed that balance today.",
